Naspers, Africa’s largest company by value, plunged the most in almost 10 years in Johannesburg trading after Chinese internet giant Tencent  posted earnings that missed analyst estimates. Naspers, which owns a 31% stake in Tencent, slumped as much as 10%, the most intraday since October 2008. The South African benchmark index dropped as much as 2.7% Wednesday, reflecting Naspers’s 18% weighting in the gauge. Read about Tencent’s results here Naspers was 6.3% lower as of 12:53 pm. Source: Bloomberg © 2018 Bloomberg